SIMPLE: train
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Train
<hw>Train</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Training</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>trahiner</ets>,
<ets>tra⟦ium⟧ner</ets>,F. <ets>tra⟦icir⟧ner</ets>, LL.
<ets>trahinare</ets>, <ets>trainare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>trahere</ets> to
draw. See <er>Trail</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw along; to trail; to drag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In hollow cube⟦br⟧
<qex>Training</qex> his devilish enginery.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw by persuasion, artifice, or the like; to
attract by stratagem; to entice; to allure.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If but a dozen French⟦br⟧
Were there in arms, they would be as a call⟦br⟧
To <qex>train</qex> ten thousand English to their side.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, <qex>train</qex> me not, sweet mermaid, with thy note.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This feast, I'll gage my life,⟦br⟧
Is but a plot to <qex>train</qex> you to your ruin.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To teach and form by practice; to educate; to
exercise; to discipline; <as>as, to <ex>train</ex> the militia to the
manual exercise; to <ex>train</ex> soldiers to the use of
arms.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our <qex>trained</qex> bands, which are the trustiest and most
proper strength of a free nation.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warrior horse here bred he's taught to <qex>train</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To break, tame, and accustom to draw, as
oxen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Hort.)</fld> <def>To lead or direct, and form to a
wall or espalier; to form to a proper shape, by bending, lopping, or
pruning; <as>as, to <ex>train</ex> young trees</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>trained</qex> the young branches to the right hand or to
the left.</q> <rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>To trace, as a lode or any
mineral appearance, to its head.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To train a gun</b></col> <fld>(Mil. & Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>to point it at some object either forward or else abaft the beam,
that is, not directly on the side.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To train</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To train
up</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to educate; to teach; to form by instruction or
practice; to bring up.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Train up</qex> a child in the way he should go; and when he
is old, he will not depart from it.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xxii.
6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first Christians were, by great hardships, <qex>trained
up</qex> for glory.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Train</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Train
<hw>Train</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be drilled in
military exercises; to do duty in a military company.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prepare by exercise, diet, instruction, etc., for
any physical contest; <as>as, to <ex>train</ex> for a boat
race</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Train</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Train
<hw>Train</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>train</ets>, OF.
<ets>tra⟦ium⟧n</ets>, <ets>trahin</ets>; cf. (for some of the senses) F.
<ets>traine</ets>. See <er>Train</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That which draws along; especially, persuasion, artifice, or
enticement; allurement.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Now to my
charms, and to my wily <xex>trains</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, something tied to a lure to entice a hawk;
also, a trap for an animal; a snare.</def>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With cunning <qex>trains</qex> him to entrap un wares.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is drawn along in the rear of, or after,
something; that which is in the hinder part or rear.</def> Specifically
: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>That part of a gown which trails behind the
wearer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The after part of a gun carriage;
the trail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The tail of a bird.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>train</xex> steers their flights, and turns their bodies, like the
rudder of ship.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A number of followers; a body of attendants; a
retinue; a suite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king's daughter with a lovely <qex>train</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>train</qex> are men of choice and rarest parts.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A consecution or succession of connected things; a
series.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>train</xex> of happy sentiments.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>I. Watts.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>train</qex> of ills our love would draw behind it.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rivers now⟦br⟧
Stream and perpetual draw their humid <qex>train</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Other truths require a <qex>train</qex> of ideas placed in
order.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Regular method; process; course; order; <as>as,
things now in a <ex>train</ex> for settlement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If things were once in this <qex>train</qex>, . . . our duty would
take root in our nature.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The number of beats of a watch in any certain
time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A line of gunpowder laid to lead fire to a charge,
mine, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A connected line of cars or carriages on a railroad;
-- called also <altname>railroad train</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A heavy, long sleigh used in Canada for the
transportation of merchandise, wood, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Rolling Mill)</fld> <def>A roll train; <as>as, a
12-inch <ex>train</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The aggregation of men, animals,
and vehicles which accompany an army or one of its subdivisions, and
transport its baggage, ammunition, supplies, and reserve materials of
all kinds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Roll train</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Train of
rolls</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Rolling Mill)</fld>, <cd>a set of plain or
grooved rolls for rolling metal into various forms by a series of
consecutive operations.</cd> -- <col><b>Train mile</b></col>
<fld>(Railroads)</fld>, <cd>a unit employed in estimating running
expenses, etc., being one of the total number of miles run by all the
trains of a road, or system of roads, as within a given time, or for a
given expenditure; -- called also <altname>mile run</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Train of artillery</b></col>, <cd>any number of cannon, mortars,
etc., with the attendants and carriages which follow them into the
field.</cd> <au>Campbell (Dict. Mil. Sci.).</au> -- <col><b>Train of
mechanism</b></col>, <cd>a series of moving pieces, as wheels and
pinions, each of which is follower to that which drives it, and driver
to that which follows it.</cd> -- <col><b>Train road</b></col>, <cd>a
slight railway for small cars, -- used for construction, or in
mining.</cd> -- <col><b>Train tackle</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
tackle for running guns in and out.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cars.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Train</er>,
<er>Cars</er>. At one time ⟦ldquo⟧train⟦rdquo⟧ meaning railroad train
was also referred to in the U. S. by the phrase ⟦ldquo⟧the cars⟦rdquo⟧.
In the 1913 dictionary the usage was described thus:
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Train</xex> is the word universally used in England with
reference to railroad traveling; <as>as, I came in the morning
<ex>train</ex></as>. In the United States, the phrase <xex>the
cars</xex> has been extensively introduced in the room of
<xex>train</xex>; <as>as, <ex>the cars</ex> are late; I came in <ex>the
cars</ex></as>. The English expression is obviously more appropriate,
and is prevailing more and more among Americans, to the exclusion of
<xex>the cars</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trainable</ent>⟦br⟧
